TY  - JOUR
T1  - BLIND SPOTS IN INDUSTRY AND COMPETITOR ANALYSIS: IMPLICATIONS OF INTERFIRM (MIS)PERCEPTIONS FOR STRATEGIC DECISIONS
AU  - Zajac, Edward J.
AU  - Bazerman, Max H.
Y1  - 1991/01/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1991.4278990
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1991.4278990
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 37
EP  - 56
VL  - 16
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article bridges the literatures on competitor analysis and strategic decision making by (1) introducing the notion of competitive decision making into the strategic decision-making literature and (2) embedding this notion into a framework of industry and competitor analysis. The article shows that decision makers typically have specific ?blind spots? when they consider the contingent decisions of competitors. The article identifies these blind spots and discusses how they may explain persistent, commonly observed phenomena such as industry overcapacity, new business entry failures, and acquisition premiums.
AB  - This article bridges the literatures on competitor analysis and strategic decision making by (1) introducing the notion of competitive decision making into the strategic decision-making literature and (2) embedding this notion into a framework of industry and competitor analysis. The article shows that decision makers typically have specific ?blind spots? when they consider the contingent decisions of competitors. The article identifies these blind spots and discusses how they may explain persistent, commonly observed phenomena such as industry overcapacity, new business entry failures, and acquisition premiums.
