TY  - JOUR
T1  - INFORMATION SEEKING DURING ORGANIZATIONAL ENTRY: INFLUENCES, TACTICS, AND A MODEL OF THE PROCESS
AU  - Miller, Vernon D.
AU  - Jablin, Fredric M.
Y1  - 1991/01/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1991.4278997
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1991.4278997
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 92
EP  - 120
VL  - 16
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Although information-seeking efforts during organisational entry are of critical importance to newcomers' successful organisational assimilation, the means by which new hires seek information has received scant research attention. Consequently, in this article we develop a theoretical model depicting factors that may affect newcomers' information-seeking behaviors, examine the means or tactics by which they seek information, and present a series of heuristically-oriented propositions concerning newcomers' use of these tactics.
AB  - Although information-seeking efforts during organisational entry are of critical importance to newcomers' successful organisational assimilation, the means by which new hires seek information has received scant research attention. Consequently, in this article we develop a theoretical model depicting factors that may affect newcomers' information-seeking behaviors, examine the means or tactics by which they seek information, and present a series of heuristically-oriented propositions concerning newcomers' use of these tactics.
